value.value: A gammaretrovirus that has been isolated from human biological samples and associated with familial and sporadic prostate cancer and chronic fatigue syndrome.

An in vitro molecular diagnostic test that uses gene expression profiling to analyze gene activity within a breast cancer tumor sample. It looks at the activity of 70 genes and is useful in assessing the likelihood of metastasis and recurrence.

The transfer of new understandings of disease mechanisms gained in the laboratory into the development of new methods for diagnosis, therapy, and prevention including their testing in humans and the use of observations made during clinical research to identify new avenues of research for the laboratory.
An astroblastoma, MN1-altered, characterized by the presence of high mitotic activity, cytologic atypia, and architectural distortion.

A hereditary syndrome affecting the central nervous system that is associated with lesions of the skin and retina. Representative examples include neurofibromatosis, tuberous sclerosis, von Hippel-Lindau syndrome, and Sturge-Weber syndrome.
Tumor suppressor ARF (173 aa, ~18 kDa) is encoded by the human CDKN2A gene. This protein is involved in cell cycle arrest.

label.value: Atypical Glandular Cell of Undetermined Significance
International Prognostic Scoring System (IPSS) for Myelodysplastic Syndromes

value.value: A system for scoring myelodysplasia syndrome progression risk, based on a combination of: percentage of blast cells in the bone marrow, the presence and severity of specific cytogenetic abnormalities, and the number of cytopenias in the peripheral blood.
Situated or occurring within the cranium; affecting or involving intracranial structures.
Relating to the cranium and the spinal column.
An infectious process affecting the vagina. Symptoms include pain and purulent discharge.

Inflammation of the anatomical structures of the middle ear secondary to an infectious process. Bacterial etiology is most common, but both viral and fungal pathogens are also possible. Symptoms include erythema and edema of the tympanic membrane, pain, and possibly fever. In severe infections, inflammation and edema of the structures of the middle ear can lead to perforation of the tympanic membrane secondary to the buildup of pressure in the narrow space.
Occurring during the course of a surgical procedure.
An epithelioma characterized by the absence of keratin production.
A benign neoplasm arising from the yolk sac.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic pathologic process affecting the leptomeninges of the brain.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic pathologic process affecting the leptomeninges of the spinal cord.

A neoplastic process that arises from the terminal ductal lobular unit of the breast parenchyma.  It is usually solitary and confined to a single lobular unit.  It is characterized by the presence of a monomorphic epithelial proliferation in a cribriform, micropapillary, or solid growth pattern.  Focal architectural features of low grade ductal carcinoma in situ are present.  There is an increased risk for development of invasive breast carcinoma.
The presence of brain metastasis that originates from a cancer growth in a distant anatomic site.
The pattern of a person's emotional, romantic, and/or sexual attractions.
A sexual attraction to members of the opposite sex.
A sexual attraction to members of the same sex.
A sexual attraction to members of both sexes, genders, or gender identities.

label.value: Men who have Sex with Men

value.value: Men who engage in sexual activity with other men, regardless of how they identify themselves.
A person who takes recreational drugs.
A person who injects recreational drugs.
A drug used for personal enjoyment rather than for medicinal purposes.
Situated or occurring outside the nerve or nerves.
Implantation of radioactive material in an internal anatomic site.
Efforts by doctors and other care givers to give patients the resources they need to manage their own care and make them active participants in the decision making process.
A measurement of the length of the lower leg from the top of the knee to the bottom of the heel. This measurement may be taken with a knemometer or calipers.
An immunohistochemical diagnostic test utilizing an antibody to detect IGF1R in tissues.
This gene may be involved in the regulation of cellular proliferation.

Human CMC4 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of Xq28 and is approximately 10 kb in length. This allele, which encodes Cx9C motif-containing protein 4, is involved in the modulation of cell proliferation. Aberrant expression of the gene is observed in T-cell leukemias bearing a t(X;14) translocation.
Cx9C motif-containing protein 4 (68 aa, ~8 kDa) is encoded by the human CMC4 gene. This protein plays a role in cellular proliferation.
The act of improving by expanding or enlarging or refining.
An abstract or general idea inferred or derived from specific instances.
A well-substantiated explanation of some aspect of the natural world.
Any of the numbers (or symbols) that form a product when multiplied together.
The procedure by which the measured spectrum of a mixed pixel is decomposed into a collection of constituent spectra.

value.value: A process for killing microorganisms.
An array of entities, such as light waves or particles, ordered in accordance with the magnitudes of a common physical property, such as wavelength or mass.
The measured value of a response in a recorded image produced by the intensity, abundance, or concentration of source materials.
An analysis (often in graphical form) representing the extent to which something exhibits various characteristics.
The mechanical process of breaking particles into smaller pieces via one or more particle size reduction mechanisms. Milling is the most common process used.
The reduction process performed at licensed facilities to manufacture animal feeds.
Dense fibrous connective tissue sealing the joint. It is attached to the bones and provides stability.
An autoimmune chronic skin disorder characterized by the presence of large blisters. It usually affects elderly people and tends to subside spontaneously.
A syndrome characterized by abnormal secretion of renin in conjunction with neoplastic growth occurring anywhere in the body.
